ARTICLE II. - OCCUPATION TAXES AND REGULATORY FEES[2] 

Footnotes: 
--- (2) --- 
Cross reference— Taxation, ch. 62. 
State Law reference— Business and occupation taxes, O.C.G.A. § 48-13-1 et seq. 

Sec. 22-31. - Occupation tax required. 
Each person engaged in any business, trade, profession or occupation in the unincorporated areas of the county, whether with a location in the unincorporated areas of the county or in the case of an out-of-state business with no location in Georgia exerting substantial efforts within the state pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 48-13-7, shall pay an occupation tax for such business, trade, profession or occupation, which tax and any applicable registration shall be displayed in a conspicuous place in the place of business, if the taxpayer has a permanent business location in the county. If the taxpayer has no permanent business location in the county, such business tax registration shall be shown to the county clerk, the county sheriff, or their respective designees. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 1) 
Sec. 22-32. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
Administrative fee means a component of an occupation tax that approximates the reasonable cost of handling and processing the occupation tax. 
Dominant line means the type of business, within a multiple-line business, that the greatest amount of income is derived from. 
Location of office means any structure or vehicle where a business, profession or occupation is conducted, but shall not include a temporary or construction work site that serves a single customer or project or a vehicle used for sales or delivery by a business or practitioner of a profession or occupation that has a location or office. 
Occupation tax means a tax levied on persons, partnerships, corporations or other entities for engaging in an occupation, profession or business for revenue-raising purposes. 
Practitioner of profession or occupation means one who by state law requires state licensure regulating such profession or occupation. The term does not include a practitioner who is an employee of a business if the business pays an occupation tax. 
Regulatory fees means payments, whether designated as license fees, permit fees, or by another name, required by the county as an exercise of its police power and as a part of or an aid to regulation of an occupation, profession or business. The amount of a regulatory fee shall approximate the reasonable cost of the actual regulatory activity performed by the county. A regulatory fee may not include an administrative fee. Development impact fees as defined by O.C.G.A. § 36-71-2(8) or other costs or conditions of zoning or land development are not regulatory fees. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 2) 
Cross reference— Definitions generally, § 1-2. 
Sec. 22-33. - Administrative and regulatory fee structure; occupation tax structure. 
(a)  A nonprorated, nonrefundable administrative fee as stated in the schedule of fees and charges shall be required on all business and occupation tax accounts for the initial start-up, renewal, or reopening of those accounts. 
(b)  A regulatory fee as stated in the schedule of fees and charges is imposed as authorized under O.C.G.A. § 48-13-9. Such regulatory fee does not include an administrative fee. Such regulatory fee shall apply to each business listed as follows: 
(1)  Building and construction contractors and subcontractors; 
(2)  Carnivals; 
(3)  Taxicab and limousine operators; 
(4)  Tattoo artists; 
(5)  Stables; 
(6)  Shooting galleries and firearm ranges; 
(7)  Scrap metal processors; 
(8)  Pawnbrokers; 
(9)  Food service establishments; 
(10)  Dealers in precious metals; 
(11)  Firearms dealers; 
(12)  Peddlers; 
(13)  Parking lots; 
(14)  Nursing and personal care homes; 
(15)  Modeling agencies; 
(16)  Massage parlors; 
(17)  Landfills; 
(18)  Auto and motorcycle racing; 
(19)  Boardinghouses; 
(20)  Businesses that provide appearance bonds; 
(21)  Boxing and wrestling promoters; 
(22)  Hotels and motels; 
(23)  Hypnotists; 
(24)  Handwriting analysts; 
(25)  Health clubs, gyms, and spas; 
(26)  Fortunetellers; 
(27)  Garbage collectors; 
(28)  Escort services; 
(29)  Burglar and fire alarm installers; and 
(30)  Locksmiths. 
(c)  The inspection department shall impose permit fees for construction and development in compliance with ordinances and regulations for the unincorporated areas of the county. It is the express intent of the board of commissioners that this article shall not affect existing ordinances in any manner whatsoever. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 3) 
Sec. 22-34. - Occupation tax levied; restrictions. 
(a)  An occupation tax shall be levied upon those businesses and practitioners of professions and occupations with one or more locations or offices in the unincorporated areas of the county and upon the applicable out-of-state businesses with no location or office in Georgia pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 48-13-7 based upon the number of employees of the business or practitioner. 
(b)  The tax rate determined by the number of employees for each business, trade, profession, or occupation is as follows: 

 
(c)  No business or practitioner shall be required to pay more than one occupation tax for each of its locations. 
(d)  No occupation tax shall be required from those real estate brokers, real estate agents or real estate companies whose offices are located outside the unincorporated areas of the county and who sell property inside the unincorporated areas of the county. 
(e)  Only those employees who work in the unincorporated areas of the county shall be counted for purposes of determination of the amount of applicable occupation taxes under this article. 
(f)  In the case of a business subject to occupation tax for a calendar year, which business was not conducted for any period of time in the unincorporated areas of the county during the preceding year, the owner, proprietor, manager or executive officer of the business liable for occupation tax shall estimate the number of employees from the commencing date to the end of the calendar year; and such occupation tax shall be paid according to that estimate. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 4) 
Sec. 22-35. - Paying occupation tax of business with no location in state. 
Registration and assessment of an occupation tax is imposed on those businesses and practitioners of professions with no location or office in the state if the business' largest dollar volume of business in the state is in the county, and the business or practitioner: 
(1)  Has one or more employees or agents who exert substantial efforts within the jurisdiction of the unincorporated areas of the county for the purpose of soliciting business or serving customers or clients; or 
(2)  Owns personal or real property that generates income and is located within the jurisdiction of the unincorporated areas of the county. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 5) 
Sec. 22-36. - Each line of business to be identified on business registration. 
The business registration of each business operated in the county shall identify the dominant line of business the business conducts. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 6) 
Sec. 22-37. - Professionals as classified in state law. 
(a)  Practitioners of professions as described in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-9(c)(1)—(18) shall elect as their entire occupation tax one of the following: 
(1)  The occupation tax based on number of employees as set forth in section 22-34. 
(2)  A tax of $400.00 per practitioner who is licensed to provide the service, such tax to be paid at the practitioner's office or location; however, a practitioner paying according to this subsection shall not be required to provide information to the local government relating to the gross receipts of the business of practitioner nor as to the number of employees of the practitioner. The per-practitioner fee applies to each person in the business who qualifies as a practitioner under the state's regulatory guidelines and framework. 
(b)  Such election shall be made on or before February 1, 1998. Such election shall be changed for subsequent calendar years only by written request filed by the professional on or before February 1 of the year in which the election is to be changed. 
(c)  Examples of businesses and practitioners of professions and occupations subject to this section include but are expressly not limited to the following: 
(1)  Lawyers; 
(2)  Physicians licensed under O.C.G.A. § 43-34-1 et seq.; 
(3)  Osteopaths licensed under O.C.G.A. § 43-34-1 et seq.; 
(4)  Chiropractors; 
(5)  Podiatrists; 
(6)  Dentists; 
(7)  Optometrists; 
(8)  Psychologists; 
(9)  Veterinarians; 
(10)  Landscape architects; 
(11)  Land surveyors; 
(12)  Practitioners of physiotherapy; 
(13)  Public accountants; 
(14)  Embalmers; 
(15)  Funeral directors; 
(16)  Civil, mechanical, hydraulic or electrical engineers; 
(17)  Architects; 
(18)  Marriage and family therapists; 
(19)  Social workers and professional counselors; 
(20)  Dealers of motor vehicles, as defined in O.C.G.A. § 10-1-622(1); and 
(21)  Any other business, profession or occupation for which state licensure or registration is required by state law, unless the state law regulating such business, profession or occupation specifically allows for regulation by local governments. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 7) 
Sec. 22-38. - Practitioners exclusively practicing for a government. 
Any practitioner whose office is maintained by and who is employed in practice exclusively by the United States, the state, a municipality or county of the state, instrumentalities of the United States, the state, or a municipality or county of the state shall not be required to obtain a license or pay an occupation tax. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 8) 
Sec. 22-39. - Purpose and scope of tax. 
The occupation tax levied in this article is for revenue purposes only and is not for regulatory purposes, nor is the payment of the tax made a condition precedent to the practice of any such profession, trade or calling. The occupation tax only applies to those businesses and occupations covered by the provisions of O.C.G.A. §§ 48-13-5—48-13-26. All other applicable businesses and occupations are taxed by the local government pursuant to the pertinent general and/or local law and ordinance. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 9) 
Sec. 22-40. - Business license issued; violation for failure to pay and obtain license. 
(a)  Upon payment of an occupation tax, administrative fee and regulatory fee, or any such combination as required in this article, the applicant shall receive a business license, which shall be displayed in a conspicuous place in the place of business if the taxpayer has a permanent business location in the county. If the taxpayer has no permanent business location in the county, such business license shall be shown to any police officer or enforcement officer of the county upon request. 
(b)  It shall be a violation of this article for any person to operate or conduct a business, trade, profession or occupation in the county, whether with a location in the unincorporated areas of the county or in the case of an out-of-state business with no location in the state exerting substantial efforts within the state pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 48-13-7, or to exercise, conduct or operate any business subject to a regulatory fee, without having first filed a return for payment of the applicable occupation tax, administrative fee and regulatory fee (or such combination as is applicable to such person) paid the applicable occupation tax, regulatory fee and administrative fee (or such combination as is applicable to such person), and obtained and displayed a business license. Where a person is subject to paying an occupation tax, administrative fee and regulatory fee under this article, such person shall obtain one business license, which shall reflect payment of all such charges. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 10) 
Sec. 22-41. - When tax due and payable; effect of transacting business when tax delinquent. 
(a)  Each occupation tax, administrative fee and regulatory fee shall be payable for the calendar year 1998 and succeeding calendar years thereafter unless otherwise specifically provided. This registration and occupation tax shall be payable on January 1 of each year and shall, if not paid by January 15 of each year, be subject to penalties for delinquencies prescribed in this article. On any new profession, trade or business begun in the unincorporated area of the county in 1998, or in succeeding years thereafter, the administrative fee, regulatory fee and occupation tax, as applicable, shall be delinquent if not obtained immediately upon beginning business, and a penalty of $50.00 shall be imposed. The tax registration provided in this section shall be issued by the revenue collection officer; and if any person whose duty it is to obtain a registration shall, after the registration, occupation tax, regulatory fee, or administrative fee becomes delinquent, transacts or offers to transact, in the unincorporated areas of the county, any of the kind of profession, trade or business subject to this article without having first obtained registration, such offender shall, upon conviction by the magistrate court, be punished by a fine not to exceed $500.00, or imprisonment not to exceed ten days, either or both, in the discretion of the judge of the court. 
(b)  In addition to the above remedies specified in subsection (a) of this section, the sheriff may proceed to collect in the same manner as provided by law for tax executions. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 11) 
Sec. 22-42. - Exemption on grounds that business is operated for charitable purpose. 
No business on which a business registration or occupation tax is levied by this article shall be exempt from the registration or tax on the ground that such business is operated for a charitable purpose unless 75 percent or more of the entire proceeds from the business are devoted to such purpose. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 12) 
Sec. 22-43. - Evidence of state licensure required if applicable; state licensure to be displayed. 
(a)  Each person who is licensed by the secretary of state pursuant to O.C.G.A. tit. 43 shall provide evidence of proper and current state licensure before the county registration may be issued. 
(b)  Each person who is licensed by the state shall post the state license in a conspicuous place in the licensee's place of business and shall keep the license there at all times while the license remains valid. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 13) 
Sec. 22-44. - Evidence of qualification required if applicable. 
Any business required to obtain health permits, bonds, certificates of qualification, certificates of competency, or any other regulatory matter shall first, before the issuance of a county business registration, show evidence that such requirements have been met. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 14) 
Sec. 22-45. - Establishment of revenue collection agency; revenue collection agent; subpoena and arrest powers. 
(a)  Within and as a part of the county business license and inspection department, there is established a revenue collection agency, which shall have the responsibility for the administration of this article, including but not limited to preparing and taking applications, collecting fees, inspection and regulation of applicants, reviewing and approving or denying applications, and the issuing of business registrations under this article. 
(b)  The head of the county business license and inspection department shall also serve as head of the revenue collection agency and shall serve as the revenue collection agent. The revenue collection agent and his duly designated officers and inspectors, or his successors in office, shall be classified as deputy marshals-business inspectors with full subpoena and arrest powers in conjunction with any violation pertaining to this article. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 15) 
Sec. 22-46. - Businesses not covered by this article. 
(a)  The following businesses are not covered by the provisions of this article but may be assessed an occupation tax or other type of tax pursuant to the provisions of other general laws of the state or by local law: 
(1)  Those businesses regulated by the state public service commission. 
(2)  Those electric service businesses organized under O.C.G.A. § 46-3-1 et seq. 
(3)  Any farm operation for the production from or on the land of agricultural products, but not including agribusiness. 
(4)  Cooperative marketing associations governed by O.C.G.A. § 2-10-105. 
(5)  Insurance companies governed by O.C.G.A. § 33-8-8 et seq. 
(6)  Motor common carriers governed by O.C.G.A. § 46-7-15. 
(7)  Those businesses governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-5-355 (businesses that purchase carload lots of guano, meats, meal, flour, bran, cottonseed, or cottonseed meal and hulls). 
(8)  Agricultural products and livestock raised in the state governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-5-356. 
(9)  Depository financial institutions governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-6-93. 
(10)  Facilities operated by a charitable trust governed by O.C.G.A. § 48-13-55. 
(11)  Any state or local authority or nonprofit organization. 
(b)  The county shall not be authorized to require the payment of a fee in any amount by a business or practitioner for the cost of ascertaining whether such a business or practitioner has paid an occupation tax to another local government. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 16) 
Sec. 22-47. - Occupation tax inapplicable where prohibited by law or provided for pursuant to other existing law. 
An occupation tax shall not apply to the gross receipts of any part of a business where such levy is prohibited or exempted by the laws of the state or of the United States. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 17) 
Sec. 22-48. - Occupation tax limitations. 
(a)  The county shall not require the payment of more than one occupation tax for each location of a person. 
(1)  If a person with no location or office in the county provides to the county proof of payment of a local business or occupation tax in another state that purports to tax the person's gross receipts in this state, the person shall be exempt from the occupation tax levied by this article. 
(2)  A person who has locations or offices elsewhere in the state who is subject to occupation tax by more than one local government in the state shall be subject to occupation tax by the county unless the person provides documentation to the county of current payment of an occupation tax, measured by the gross receipts of the person, to other state local governments. 
(b)  If a person commences business in the county on or after July 1 of any year, the county shall be authorized to levy the customary rate on the gross receipts of the business or practitioner from the date of commencement of the business. The administrative fee authorized by this article shall not be reduced for any such business commencing on or after July 1 of any year. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 18) 
Sec. 22-49. - Businesses at more than one location. 
Wherever a business or occupation is conducted at more than one location or place within the county, each such location shall be considered a separate business for the purpose of the occupation tax imposed by this article. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 19) 
Sec. 22-50. - Liability of officers and agents; registration required; failure to obtain. 
All persons subject to the occupation tax levy pursuant to this article shall be required to obtain the necessary registration for the business as described in this article, and in default thereof the officer or agent soliciting for or representing such persons shall be subject to the same penalty as other persons who fail to obtain a registration. Every person commencing business in the county after January 1 of each year shall likewise obtain the registration provided for in this section before commencing business. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 20) 
Sec. 22-51. - When registration and tax due and payable; effect of transacting business when tax delinquent. 
(a)  Each registration shall be for the calendar year in which the registration was obtained unless otherwise specifically provided. There is imposed a penalty upon each business that fails to apply for and obtain and appropriate business registration and pay all taxes and fees as provided in this article before January 15 of each year. Each person commencing business in the unincorporated areas of the county after January 1 of each year shall obtain the registration required before commencing such business. Any person transacting or offering to transact in any unincorporated areas of the county any business, trade, profession or occupation without first having obtained the registration shall be subject to the penalties provided in section 22-52. These penalties shall be in addition to all other penalties, civil and criminal provided in this article, and may be collected by the remedies provided in this article for the collection of the occupation tax, and shall have the same lien and priority as the occupation tax to which the penalty is applied. 
(b)  The registration provided for in this article shall be issued by the revenue collection officer; and if any person whose duty it is to obtain a registration shall, after the occupation tax becomes delinquent, transact or offer to transact, in the unincorporated areas of the county, any kind of business, trade, profession or occupation without having first obtained registration, such offender shall be subject to the penalties provided. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 21) 
Sec. 22-52. - Due date; court penalty and interest. 
A penalty is imposed on each business and practitioner of an occupation that fails to apply for and obtain appropriate registration and to pay any and all regulatory and administrative fees and occupation taxes required by this article. This penalty shall be in the amount of $50.00. When such regulatory and administrative fees and occupation taxes remain due and unpaid beyond 30 calendar days from the due date of the tax or fee, the total penalty shall be $100.00. Penalties shall be in addition to any other penalties, civil or criminal, that may be applicable. Such penalties should become effective when such regulatory and administrative fees and occupation taxes remain due and unpaid for 15 days from the due date of the tax or fee. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 22; Res. No. Z05-033, 9-23-2005) 
Sec. 22-53. - Criminal penalty for violation of this article. 
Any person violating any provision of this article shall, upon conviction before the magistrate court, be fined in an amount not exceeding $500.00 or imprisoned for a period not exceeding ten days, either or both, in the discretion of the judge. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 23) 
Sec. 22-54. - Inspection of records. 
The revenue collection agency of the county, through its officers, agents, employees or representatives, may inspect the books or records of any business pertaining to employees of the business or person for which the returns are made. The revenue collection agent shall have the right to inspect the books or records for the business for which the return was made in the county; and upon demand of the revenue collection agent, such books or records shall be submitted for inspection by the revenue collection agent or his designee within 30 days. Failure to submit such books or records within the 30-day period shall be grounds for revocation of the tax registration currently existing to do business in the county. Adequate records shall be kept in the county for examination by the revenue collection agent at that officer's discretion. If after examination of the books and records it is determined that a deficiency occurs as a result of underreporting, a penalty of $150.00 shall be assessed for the period delinquent. The right of inspection shall be limited to those records that reflect the number of employees of the person, business, trade, occupation or profession of the business. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 24) 
Sec. 22-55. - Confidentiality. 
Information provided by a person to the county for the purpose of determining the applicability and the amount of the occupation tax or the levy or collection of the occupation tax levied pursuant to this article is confidential and exempt from disclosure. Such information may be provided by the governing authority of another local government for occupation tax purposes or pursuant to court order or for the purpose of collecting the occupation tax or prosecution for failure or refusal to pay an occupation tax. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 25) 
Sec. 22-56. - Revocation. 
Failure of any person to pay an applicable administrative fee, regulatory fee, occupation tax, or any part of a tax, before it becomes delinquent, or upon the failure to permit inspection of books as required, shall result in any business tax certificates or regulatory fee certificates granted by the county under this article permitting such person to do business in the unincorporated areas of the county for the current year being automatically revoked without any further action required of the county. No new occupation tax certificate or regulatory fee certificate shall be granted by the county for the operation of a business for which any part of the occupation tax or fees required in this article are unpaid, nor shall such certificates be issued to a person who has failed to submit adequate records for inspection as required by section 22-54. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 26) 
Sec. 22-57. - Filing of occupation tax returns. 
Any persons, their managers, agents or employees, who do business in the unincorporated areas of the county, after the registration for the business has been revoked, are required to make occupation tax returns in a form to make such returns within the time and manner provided in this article, who refuse to amend such returns so as to set forth the truth, or who shall make false returns; and any persons, their managers, agents or employees who refuse to permit an inspection of books and may charge when the officers, agents, employees or representatives of the county request such inspection, during normal business hours, for the purpose of determining the accuracy of the returns provided for in this article, shall be subject to penalties provided in this article. In the case of those practitioners where the local government cannot suspend the right of the practitioner to conduct business, the imposition of civil penalties shall be permitted and pursued by the local government as in the case of a delinquent occupation tax. These penalties shall consist of either ten percent of the amount due or a fine of $50.00, whichever is less, as determined by the revenue collection agency. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 27) 
Sec. 22-58. - Execution; liens. 
(a)  The revenue collection agent or his designee, upon any tax or installment of any tax becoming delinquent and remaining unpaid, shall issue an execution for the amount of the tax against the person liable for the tax, including interest at the rate of 1.5 percent per month accruing on the tax. The lien shall cover the property in the unincorporated areas of the county of the person liable for the tax, all as provided by ordinances of the county and the laws of the state. The lien for the occupation tax shall become fixed on and date from the time that such tax or installment becomes delinquent. The execution shall be levied by the sheriff upon the property of the defendant located in such jurisdiction, and sufficient property shall be advertised and sold to pay the amount of the execution, with interest and costs added. All other related proceedings shall be as provided by ordinances of the county and the laws of the state; and the defendants at execution shall have the rights of defense, by affidavit of illegality of the tax or otherwise as provided by the applicable laws of the state in regard to tax executions. 
(b)  When a nulla bona entry has been entered by the proper authority upon execution issued by the county against any person defaulting on an occupation tax, the person against whom the entry was made shall not be allowed or entitled to have or collect any fees or charges whatsoever for services rendered after the entry of the nulla bona. If at any time after the entry of the nulla bona has been made, the person against whom the execution pays the tax in full, together with all interest penalties and costs accrued on the tax, the person may collect any fees and charges for services and goods due the person as though the person had never defaulted in the payment of the taxes. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 28) 
Sec. 22-59. - Public hearings required. 
(a)  In any year when revenue from occupation taxes is greater than revenue from occupation taxes for the preceding year for the county, the county shall hold one or more public hearings as a part of the process of determining how to use the additional revenue derived from such occupation taxes. This hearing shall be held pursuant to the requirements of O.C.G.A. § 48-13-28. 
(b)  The board of commissioners shall conduct at least one public hearing before adopting any future ordinance or resolution regarding the occupation tax as required in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-6(c). 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 29) 
Sec. 22-60. - Applications of provisions to prior ordinance. 
This article does not repeal or affect the enforcement of any part of any ordinance heretofore passed where taxes levied under such prior ordinance have not been paid in full. So much and such parts of ordinances heretofore and hereinafter passed as provided for the issuing and enforcing of execution for any tax or assessment required by such ordinances, or that imposed fines or penalties for the nonpayment of such tax, or for failure to pay regulatory fees provided for in such ordinances, or failure to comply with any other provisions of this article, shall continue and remain in force until such tax, regulatory fee or assessment shall be fully paid. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 30) 
Sec. 22-61. - Amendment; repeal of provisions. 
This article shall be subject to amendment or repeal, in whole or in part, at any time; and no such amendment or repeal shall be construed to deny the right of the board of commissioners to assess and collect any of the taxes or other charges prescribed. The amendment may increase or lower the amounts and tax rates of any occupation and may change their classification. Payment of any occupation tax provided for shall not be construed as prohibiting the levy or collection by the board of commissioners of additional occupation taxes upon the same person, property or business. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 31) 
Sec. 22-62. - Option to establish exemption or reduction in occupation tax. 
The board of commissioners may by subsequent ordinance or resolution provide for an exemption or reduction in occupation taxes or a credit against occupation taxes owed to one or more types of businesses or practitioners of occupations or professions as part of a plan for economic development or attracting, encouraging or maintaining selected types of businesses or practitioners of selected occupations or professions. Such exemptions or reductions in occupation taxes shall not be arbitrary or capricious, and the reasons shall be set forth in the minutes of the board of commissioners. Such exemptions, reductions or credits may include but shall not be limited to those exemptions, reductions or credits more particularly set out in O.C.G.A. § 48-13-10(f)(2). 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 32) 
Sec. 22-63. - Conflicts between specific and general provisions. 
Where there is an apparent conflict in this article between specific and general provisions, it is the intention of this article that the specific shall control. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 33) 
Sec. 22-64. - No limitation of authority of board of commissioners. 
Nothing in this article shall be construed to limit the authority of the board of commissioners to regulate the exercise of business in any unincorporated areas of the county and, where authorized by federal, state, or local law or ordinance, to deny persons seeking a business registration or license, or both; nor shall this article in any way limit the authority of the board of commissioners to establish ordinances or regulations setting forth conditions for the registration or licensure of businesses, trades, occupations or professions. Nothing in this article is intended, nor shall it be construed, to limit the police powers of the county with respect to business practices as they may be established by federal, state or local law, ordinances or regulations. 
(Ord. of 1-8-1998, § 34) 
Secs. 22-65—22-99. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE III. - MOBILE FOOD TRUCKS 

Sec. 22-100. - Mobile food trucks. 
Mobile food trucks shall be allowed to sell, serve, and deliver food and food-related items within the unincorporated areas of Lee County. Any such mobile food truck, whether owned by an individual or legal entity, shall only be authorized to operate as a mobile food truck in accord with this section if the person or legal entity owning the mobile food truck obtains an appropriate permit or license from the Lee County Health Department and pays the applicable occupation taxes and regulatory fees imposed pursuant to chapter 22, article II of the Lee County Code. 
(Ord. of 12-8-2015(3))

